WRITING.TEXT.Element:Text: I agree with your first argument, I don't agree with your second: I'm part of creating a new school program and one of its' main points is to understand WHY and about WHAT are you studying. When a student knows the worth and the weight of the knowledge they're receiving, they put more time, energy and effort into writing it down, digging deeper and memorising. Or less, depends on the student themself. Math is important not only to find out how much your bacon costs in the store with -25% off, it's also for logical and tactical thinking, it introduces us to physics, paradoxes, and such phenomena as equality, balance, and etc. This knowledge is pretty mandatory and as far as I know people who put time and effort to understand the rules of math (not necessarily sitting till 2 am trying to solve the square root of 82847472, as an example), are a lot more logical and have a better perception of most situations involving risks. That's why we're encouraging our students, especially those preparing for exams, to dedicate 95% of their studying time into formulas and their relativity with other equations, knowing how and when to use the formulas.

WRITING.TITLE: b' '
WRITING.TEXT.Element:Text: 3 eating disorders at the same time. Every step I took was all to lose weight. Every movement I did was unnecessarily more complex to burn. Doing laundry? Swing the clothes. Tired? No I'm not, cannot sit. When I'd be home alone, I would run around the house till someone came back. The worst part was that I knew I'm deteriorating and doing this to myself. Because I realised it, I had couple attempts at self-de@th, you feel so hopeless, everyday was terrific, I was dying.  But what saved me was ignorance. Stopped checking nutritional value stickers. That was the main ingredient of my successful and on-going recovery. It was weird, because in my heart I knew I was tired, and one night I just said \xe2\x80\x9cf#ck it\xe2\x80\x9d and the next day I ate stuff I wanted to eat\xe2\x80\x9d. It was just as painful as at the peak of my EDs, but when \xe2\x80\x9cextreme hunger\xe2\x80\x9d kicked in I felt unstoppable. Gained around 40 pounds and was close to a healthy BMI. Had some potential relapses after that, but I still choose to eat than not to eat.

WRITING.TEXT.Element:Text: So probably not the best place to ask, but I just need someone's advice who went through this. I'm recovering from a restrictive eating disorder and I'm currently in weight gain. I've been aware of things like extreme hunger and hypermetabolism, and I got both, but like heck I can't sleep at all cuz I wake up after like 10 minutes in a pool of sweat. Mind you, I sleep with a fully open window, it's like 20 F outside, sleep shirtless and pantless with no blanket and I'm losing my mind. I feel like at this point I'll need freaking ice packs at night. Does anyone know how to ease these night sweats? I was treated for insomnia, I don't want to disturb my sleeping cycle again
